 of Ministers which, in a country like this, is attended with so many salutary consequences. The review of Bentham is also able and in-teresting. It goes far to make us acquainted with a man whose high talents, and republican virtues, will make him, the moment we are deprived of him, the boast of his country. Another article of considerable interest is that upon Junius. There seems to be very little room now left for doubting that the intrepid and elegant Junius is no other than the honourable, useful and distinguished SIR PHILLIP FRANCIS. The review of MR PHILLIPS'S Speeches has a something in it which gives us pain and distaste. The remarks are too often just; but there is more of bitterness than we think was called for. There may be a meretricious love of ornament in MR PHILLIPS'S style of oratory; but his fire and freedom, his patriotism and youth, might have secured him softer treatment. His very faults lean to virtue's side.",review,6.png
