 to put his learned adversaries to the blush, and impressed with sentiments of reverence for the Constitution, which gave vigour to his faculties, and made him irresistible in its defence. Of such energies are the friends of freedom ! So devoted are they all to the privileges for which their forefathers bled, and such an example of firmness which many of them, if called forth, display, though few perhaps could be found with equal resources and equal talent. Let us, on the present occasion, be grateful to our ancestors for the noble institution of Trial by Jury !–What a glorious example did those three successive Panels give of the discharge of the duty entrusted to them of passing between the King and the subject–and of deciding according to their conscience, not according to the dictum of a Magistrate ! When three distinct sets of Jurors have thus successively pronounced on the alleged libel of those Parodies, who shall say that they were not innocent of intention ? It is the province of Jurors to search for the intention, which makes the body of the crime, for it is a maxim of law, ""Actus non fit reum nisi mons sit rea."" We cannot add any thing to Mr HONE's own luminous ar-gument ; but we must express our gratitude to Mr WOOLER and Mr PEARSON, for having so seasonably brought into question the defective state of the register book of persons qualified in the City of London to sit on Special Juries. This is the first appearance of Juris struck from a book fully and fairly made out; and though we think that in criminal cases there ought to be no distinction between special and common Juries, since a misdemeanour that is not palpable to the understanding of twelve common men is no misdemeanour at all ; yet it is evi-dently of the utmost importance to the well-being of society, that in cases of libel, at least, the Jury should be struck im-partially, and that the panel should not be taken from a set of men that make a lucrative trade of trying causes. ",article,11.png
