eart. This was its great virtue. Coming from a penetrating and powerful judgment, it carried home conviction to the judgment of others. This was its great value. But the qualities which command-ed the greatest admiration, were the creative power of expression, and the moral fearlessness with which the preacher went forward in his purpose, without shrinking at any human consideration, or turning in the smallest degree to the right or the left. Here ""Richard was himself again."" Here DR CHALMERS shewed us practically what a Christian Preacher should be; and in his clear definition of Chris-tian charity, and in his powerful and feeling appeal to its principles as it ought to affect the practice of all, he evinced his possession of qua-lities which put it in his power not only to make amends for his late aberration, but also to disarm censure its sting. The publication of this Discourse, we are sure, would add more to his reputation than was lost by the last. But independently of all regard to himself, he owes the publication of this Charity Sermon to his country. It would be conferring a benefit generally; and to Ireland, in particular, it would be of very great advantage. It would make the heart of every true Irishman leap with joy; and while it would tend powerfully to root out prejudices, it would also sow the seeds of love, and peace, and charity.",article,14.png
