ving practised himself, he bequeathed as a legacy to his friends and followers) were zeal, perseverance, and disinterestedness in the maintenance of the doctrines that secured the liberties of our country, and would, in universal, give happiness to mankind. The Times may think, that as every question has two sides, it is better to be of both, to learn which is the best. So to be both for taxes and against them–both to support Ministers and to oppose them–both to applaud peace and condemn it–to abet persecution and de-cry it–like Sir Bullface Doubleface, who thought it prudent to take a brief both from plaintiff and defendant, that he might get to the bottom of the case, is prudent manoeuvring. Be it so! We incur from The Times and its associate MR COBBETT the imputation of being the constant organ of men who stand up for justice, liberty, and humanity; and it shall be our pride and study through life to deserve what they consider an oblo-quy.",article,28.png
