 published for centuries without any prosecution. The Antijacobin poetry of MR CANNING is one continued and offensive parody from beginning to end; and even the speeches of LORD ELDON contain much grosser allusions, than are to be found in the Litany or Catechism published by Mr Hone. These, however, were all on the side of corruption and in ridicule of liberty, and were, there-fore, to be held up as pieces of admirable wit and humour; but as soon as a poor and friendless individual thought of meeting Ministry on their own ground, and of attacking them with their own weapons, then all the vengeance of the law was to be hurled on his devo-ted head. But thanks to the ability and public spirit of MR HONE, defeat and disgrace have recoiled on them-selves; and the Juries of England have shewn that a parodist for the people is at least entitled to the same protection, as the parodists of an unprincipled and in-capable administration. The discussions in the French Chamber of Deputies, on the project of the law relative to the Freedom of the Press, have at length terminated. The resolution for continuing the surveillance of the Journals for an-other year was carried by a very slender majority; but an important amendment, declaring that the dis-tribution, and not the deposit of a work constitutes its publication, was carried against Ministers by a majo-rity of 11. The Dutch Government have thrown open the trade to China, and have lowered the import and export duty on Tea to a mere trifle. Belgian papers state, that the Duke of WELLING-TON has again appeared from the decision of the High Court of Brussels, in his case with the Flemish editor, to the Court of Cassation. The DUKE and SIDMOUTH, it would seem, are about alike persevering in their at-tacks on the freedom of the press. May their success be equal!
