tinction resided for some time within the palace of Holyrood, and afterwards having gone to England, a creditor, on a decreet obtained against them, raised diligence, and charged them, on an induciæ (the days which run betwixt the citation of a defen-der and the day of compearance in the action) of six days, to pay a certain debt, under pain of poinding on the expiration of the six days. The creditor, under sanction of the Bailie of the Abbey, attempting a poinding of his debtor's effects within the palace. A-gainst this proceeding a bill of suspension was presented to the Court of Session, complaining, 1st, That as the Noble complainer was furth of Scotland, the charge ought to have been on an induciar of sixty days; 2d, That it was illegal to execute a poinding within the sanctuary; and 3d, It was particularly unlawful to do so with-in the Royal Palace. On considering the bill, the Lord Ordinary refused it, ""to the effect that the respondent (creditor) may execute his poinding, re-serving all objections to its validity."" The suspender petitioned the Court against that judgment; which petition was ordered to be answered, and, while this order was current, the creditor endeavoured to carry through a new poind-ing upon a charge of sixty days; whereupon a second bill of sus-pension was presented for the noble Lord, and also a bill of sus-pension by the Officers of State, complaining of the poinding with-in the Palace; both of these bills the Lord Ordinary refused; against which interlocutor the noble Lord and the Officers of State, complainers, petitioned the Inne-r House.",article,46.png
