oly Allies, not satis-fied with extirpating liberty from the old continent, were seeking pretexts to extend their iron tyranny to the new, as if they seriously purposed to suffer no government to exist on the face of the globe which could be a reproach to their own gloomy despotisms. The United States, though wisely averse to war, saw that the moment for taking a de-cided part was come, and with a boldness which has delighted the friends of liberty, as much as it will astound its enemies, they have announced, by the organ of their go-vernment, that they will consider the first attempt of the Holy Allies to extend their system to any part of the Ame-rican continent as an act of hostility to them. Such is the real import, though not the express words, of what is stated by the president. The step is very decided–and we ven-ture to think very wise–in their circumstances. If the neu-trality of Britain and the United States could have been de-pended on, the weakness of the new governments in America certainly presented a tempting opportunity for the Holy Allies to establish their power in the western world. Such an attempt on their part must have sooner or later involved them in a war with the United States, and it was therefore wise in the latter to announce their intentions before the other parties were so far committed that they could not draw back. After the subjugation of Italy and Spain the Holy Confederacy had really some reason to believe, that the terror of their name would compel all nations either to crouch under their feet, or to witness their atrocious aggres-sions in a state of ""dignified neutrality."" The conduct of the American Government will cure them of this illusion. We subscribe to the Courier's opinions, that we shall hear no more of Congress to settle the affairs of South Ame-rica. We have put the passages of the speech which refer par-ticularly to this subject in Italics, and shall not therefore repeat them here. They deserve consideration, and the reader will see that they fully warrant the conclusions we have drawn from them. The constitution of the American Government affords us additional reasons for putting entire confidence in the determination announced by the Presi-dent. The power of making war and peace is vested not in the Executive but in Congress; and hence, in this case, and indeed in all measure of importance, the President consults the leading men in the Legislature, and adopts no resolu-tion without their concurrence. This first magistrate is in fact an organ of the public voice as much as either House of Congress, and we may rest assured that in this instance he has not expressed his own sentiments merely, but the sentiments of the American people. There is no doubt that the resolute tone adopted by the American Government will have an effect upon our own; and that our ministers will now find it consistent with their prudence, and their love of peace, to hold a more decided language. Some of the other statements in the President's Message are deserving of notice. He takes care to dwell upon the flourishing condition of the army and navy, the fine state of the military academy, fortresses, and manufactories of arms, the devotion of the nation to the defence of their in-stitutions, and what presents the most striking contrast to the care of legitimate monarchies, the flourishing state of the finances, so that the Americans are actually paying off debt rapidly, while the Holy Allies are adding to their in-cumbrances from year to year. He proposes that the Slave Trade should be declared piracy, and that the system of allowing an enemy's trading ships to pass unmolested in war–a system long ago recommended by FRANKLIN, and act-ed upon by the French during their late attack on Spain–should be universally adopted. Altogether we warmly recommend the speech to a careful perusal. It is most justly characterised by the Times as a document of a very difference description from those flimsy communica-tions called King's speeches, addressed to Lords and Com-mons, Peers and Deputies, in kingdoms nearer home. The latter–""as sources of intelligence–as indications of policy–as keys to national history, have of late years dwindled to nothing, realising with curious accuracy TAL-LEYRAND'S definition of the use of language–'an instrument for concealing men's thoughts.' The genius of a popular government rejects these mysterious devices, which we are sorry to see practised amongst any people a-live to the natural and almost indissoluble intimacy be-tween frankness of speech and rectitude of action. The President's message of the United States is a paper breath-ing business in every line. It is at once a picture of the period elapsed since the labours of Congress were last interrupted, a prospectus for the forthcoming year, the de-tailed report of a commissioner, and the formal account of a trustee. On scarcely any occasion do we recollect a mes-sage from this high officer of the United States, delivered during a time of peace, which might not be consulted as a safe and pregnant authority for the events and politics of the crisis at which it was made public, whether with re-gard to the concerns of the Union or to those of surround-ing nations."" We have at length the pleasure to announce the expul-sion of the last remnant of the Spanish force from Colum-bia. Porto Cabello was taken by assault by Generals PAEZ and BERMUDEZ on the 8th November, and on the 10th the few Spanish troops which survived the assault, and found refuge in an island in the harbour, capitulated. Thus ended a contest which has lasted, with some pauses, since 1810, and which Spanish obstinacy has prolonged, at a vast expense of blood, for many years after every rational hope of success had vanished. For this sort of obstinacy, the effect of pride, the Spaniard has been distinguished in all ages. He is, as old PETER HEYLIN says, ""like one of those animals which, being once crept into a place, is so rooted there, that nothing but the extremity of violence can fetch him out again."" It is this disposition which makes him a bigot in religion–a despiser of foreign na-tions and foreign improvements–an inexorable enemy, who will inflict a thousand miseries upon himself for the sake of doing a small injury to his adversary. Feeble and sluggish till his passions are engaged in the quarrel, war with him then becomes ""war to the knife."" For the last fifteen years he has acted the hero wherever he was fight-ing in support of ignorance, intolerance, and oppression; and his pride and courage never deserted him till he was engaged in the cause in which the great and the wise in every age have been proud to shed their blood. Columbia has now terminated, so far as regards herself, this arduous struggle; and she has well established her title to independence by the sacrifices she has made to ob-tain it. She has broken the arm that held her in thral-dom–and will now be able to apply her whole energies to the cultivation of her vast natural resources. Possessing a fertile and boundless territory, enjoying the fullest measure",editorial_article,81.png
