or's effects within the palace. A-gainst this proceeding a bill of suspension was presented to the Court of Session, complaining, 1st, That as the Noble complainer was forth of Scotland, the charge ought to have been on an induciae of sixty days; 2d, That it was illegal to execute a poinding within the sanctuary; and 3d, It was particularly unlawful to do so with-in the Royal Palace. On considering the bill, the Lord Ordinary refused it, ""to the effect that the respondent (creditor) may execute his poinding, re-serving all objections to its validity."" The suspender positioned the Court against that judgment; which petition was ordered to be answered, and, while this order was current, the creditor endeavoured to carry through a new poind-ing upon a charge of sixty days; whereupon a second bill of sus-pension was presented for the noble Lord, and also a bill of sus-pension by the Officers of State, complaining of the poinding with-in the Palace; both of these bills the Lord Ordinary refused; against which interlocutor the noble Lord and the Officers of State, complainers, petitioned the Inner-House. On advising the petition with answers in the first bill of suspen-sion, the Court adhered to the Lord Ordinary's interlocutor, in re-spect the noble Lord had not offered caution; but their Lordships passed the noble Lord's second bill, that the question might be tried by him and by the Officers of State, whether it was legal to execute a poinding within the King's Palace? The bill of sus-pension, which had been presented for the Officers of State, was also passed by the Court to try that question, and the case was re-mitted to Lord Alloway to hear parties on their respective pleas. Having heard the cause at great length, the Lord Ordinary found the poindings competent, and sustained the creditor's right, ""In respect that there is no precedent for the sanctuary of Holyrood-house, or for the Palace, affording an protection to the effects of debtors residing therein, so us to relieve them from poinding; that the suspender's reason could apply only to the Sovereign's residence in the Palace, whose presence ought not to be disturbed by the in-trusion of persons into the Palace without his permission, or that of the keeper appointed by Him; and that the diligence in question was authorised by the Baron Bailie of the Abbey, the officer ap-pointed by the hereditary keeper of the Palace."" Petitions were presented to the Inner-House against that judg-ment, but their Lordships unanimously adhered.
