gard to ex-pected operations. We are sorry to observe from them, that sickness to a considerable extent has already ap-peared, and that apprehensions of its spreading are en-tertained. It is stated in these letters, that nothing is to be apprehended from any operations of the enemy be-tween Prome and Rangoon, and that the neareast point at which the enemy are said to be in any force, and that inconsiderable, is Shembeunghenn. Little doubt seems entertained as to the fact of their encroaching themselves strongly at Ava and Amnapoora; and it is added, with great apparent show of reason, that if the Burmese con-tinue to pursue the system they have hitherto followed, and if nothing but such a deserted place as Prom was found, no advantage of any importance can be expected from the occupation of the capital, nor can the army look or any valuables in the way of prize. We hope and trust that the fears which some of these letters hold out of an increasing sickness as the monsoon proceeds, will prove unfounded; but we shall certainly look with no little anxiety to the despatches that may be expected from Sir Archibald's head-quarters for some time to come. The arrival of the Arracan gun-boats had re-lieved the army from some apprehensions which they had begun to entertain as to the supply of provisions. The Burmese force at Shembeunghenn is said to be the relics of that defeated by General Morrison in Arracan. An attempt to penetrate from Prome to Arra-can had failed, the roads being impassable for cattle, and being with difficulty practicable to any kind of passage whatever. The rains had not seriously set in at Prome, and there had been no torrents. The river, however, is said to have filled to a considerable extent, and was on the increase. Moonshoeror is said to be in high favour at the Court of Ava, and not the slightest disposition shown towards any overtures of peace. Of the death of the Bundoolah no doubt is now entertain-ed at Prome.",article,96.png
